  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">RTL Campaign cash for work and food in Achin, Nangarhar</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">3,500 vulnerable people (500 HH) will find food support.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Currently 18.4 million Afghans are in need, and 5.1 million of them are children. One in three Afghans is acute food insecure and 50% of all children under 5 are malnourished. According to pre-harvest IPC Analysis (March&#x2019;21), 35% of the population (11 million people) are in IPC3 or worse. Furthermore, spring 2021 is expected to see a volatile and unpredictable pattern of conflict with an anticipated escalation in fighting, in line with seasonal patterns of conflict each year and worsened by the start of the withdrawal of US forces. At the same time low winter rainfall and hot temperatures associated with a La Ni&#xF1;a weather event are anticipated to drive drought-like conditions over spring, affecting rain-fed and irrigated agriculture/livestock, as well as availability of water for drinking, washing and sanitation. It is anticipated that 25 provinces, already with high levels of food insecurity and malnutrition, are likely to be most acutely affected. Furthermore, flash floods can be expected as well.&#x202F;  
The food security situation will further deteriorate throughout the year as armed conflict and security incidents will increase displacement levels heavily. Since the start of 2021, the number of armed clashes between the Taliban, the Afghan National Security Forces and Non-State Armed Groups has surged, causing displacement and loss of livelihoods across 29 out of 34 provinces of Afghanistan. From 1 January until date, 2021 116,000 people were forcibly displaced due to conflict. Under the US Biden administration since 1 May, 2021, US and NATO troops are being withdrawn from the country, leaving a power vacuum. As a result militants have launched assaults around the country, with heavy fighting reported in among other Nangarhar province. One of the affected districts is Achin, where 2 years ago ISIS was ousted. Following the departure of ISIS Cordaid started working in the area as needs were overwhelming as the area was completely isolated under ISIS. More recently Achin was once again affected by insecurity caused by fighting between the Afghan forces and Taliban resulting in (partial) destruction of community infrastructure, houses but also livelihoods of people.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To enable 3,500 vulnerable people (500 HH) who are affected by conflict and or are in IPC3+ or IPC4 in Afghanistan to meet their urgent and basic needs, directly responding to localized crisis in a coordinated, timely and principled way through cash transfers, reducing the use of negative coping mechanisms.</narrative>
  </description>
